t|344\n|align=right|206\n|-\n|[[Kumiai]] (Ti'pai)\n|align=right|328\n|align=right|185\n|-\n|[[Kickapoo people|Kikap\u00fa]] (Kikapooa)\n|align=right|251\n|align=right|144\n|-\n|[[Cochimi]] (Laym\u00f3n, mti'p\u00e1)\n|align=right|226\n|align=right|96\n|-\n|[[Ixil people|Ixil]]\n|align=right|224\n|align=right|108\n|-\n|[[Kiliwa]] (Ko'lew)\n|align=right|107\n|align=right|55\n|-\n|[[Aguacatec]]\n|align=right|59\n|align=right|27\n|-\n|Other groups<sup>2</sup>\n|align=right|728\n|align=right|337\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:left;\"|\n<small><sup>2</sup> Includes [[Opata people|Opata]], [[Soltec]] and [[Papabuco]]</small>\n|-\n|colspan= 3style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<small>Source: CDI (2000)</small> <ref name=\"http\"/>\n|}\n\n[[File:Comandanta_Ramona_by_bastian.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Comandanta Ramona]] was the ''[[nom de guerre]]'' of an officer of the [[Zapatista Army of National Liberation]] (EZLN), a [[revolutionary]] indigenous [[autonomist]] organization based in the southern [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[States of Mexico|state]] of [[Chiapas]].]]\n[[File:Mexico1980-010_hg.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Image from Mexico in 1980.]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n<sup>1</sup><small>Number of indigenous peoples that still speak their Indigenous language</small>\n\n==See also==\n[[File:Zapatista Dolls for Sale - Chamula - Chiapas - Mexico - 02 (15638772616).jpg|thumb|right|Zapatista dolls]]\n\n*[[New Spain|Colonial Mexico]]\n*[[Indigenismo in Mexico]]\n*[[Indigenous peoples of California]]\n*[[Indigenous peoples of the North American Southwest]]\n*[[Mesoamerica]]\n*[[Mesoamerican chronology]]\n*[[Mexican Indian Wars]]\n*[[Mexicans of European descent]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin|indent=yes}}<!--BEGIN biblio format. If indent param. is used,  Pls use a colon (:) instead of asterisk (*) for bullet markers in the references list -->\n: {{Cite book |author=CIA [US Central Intelligence Agency] |year=2008 |chapter=Mexico |chapterurl=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/print/mx.html |title=The 2008 World Factbook |journal=The World Factbook |edition=online |location=Washington, DC |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |issn=1553-8133 |oclc=34199805 |accessdate=2009-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417062301/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/print/mx.html |archivedate=2009-04-17 |title-link=World Factbook }}\n: {{Cite journal|author=Lizcano Fern\u00e1ndez, Francisco |date=May\u2013August 2005 |title=Composici\u00f3n \u00c9tnica de las Tres \u00c1reas Culturales del Continente Americano al Comienzo del Siglo XXI |url=http://convergencia.uaemex.mx/rev38/38pdf/LIZCANO.pdf |format=PDF online reproduction by UAEM |journal=Convergencia |location=Toluca, Mexico |publisher=[[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma del Estado de M\u00e9xico]] |volume=A\u00f1o 12 |issue=38 |pages=185\u2013232 |issn=1405-1435 |oclc=61659674 |language=es |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920172933/http://convergencia.uaemex.mx/rev38/38pdf/LIZCANO.pdf |archivedate=September 20, 2008 }}\n: {{Cite book|author=Mart\u00ednez Novo, Carmen |year=2006 |title=''Who defines indigenous? Identities, development, intellectuals and the State in Northern Mexico'' |location=New Brunswick |publisher=Rutgers University Press}}\n: {{Cite book |author=Mart\u00ednez-Torres, Mar\u00eda Elena |author2=Rosaluz P\u00e9rez Espinosa |author3=Aldo Gonz\u00e1lez Rojas |year=2008 |chapter=Mexico |title=The Indigenous World 2008 |chapter-url=http://www.iwgia.org/sw29940.asp |chapter-format=PDF online edition |editor=Katherin Wessendorf (compilation and ed.) |others=Alejandro Parellada (regional ed.) |series=International Work Group for Indigenous Affairs yearbooks |issn=1024-0217 |location=Copenhagen |publisher=[[International Work Group for Indigenous Affairs|IWGIA]], distributed by [[Transaction Publishers]] |pages=78\u201389 |isbn=978-8